Now I understand the issue. Looking at the test case `shouldCorrectCharsetForDuplicateCharsetString`:

```java
@Test
public void shouldCorrectCharsetForDuplicateCharsetString() {
    assertEquals("iso-8859-1", DataUtil.getCharsetFromContentType("text/html; charset=charset=iso-8859-1"));
}
```

The test expects that when the content type string is `"text/html; charset=charset=iso-8859-1"`, it should correctly extract `"iso-8859-1"` as the charset.

Looking at the implementation of `getCharsetFromContentType` method and the regex pattern:

```java
private static final Pattern charsetPattern = Pattern.compile("(?i)\\bcharset=\\s*\"?([^\\s;\"]*)");
```

The current regex pattern `(?i)\\bcharset=\\s*\"?([^\\s;\"]*)` finds the first occurrence of "charset=" and captures everything after it until it hits whitespace, semicolon, or quote. When it encounters `"charset=charset=iso-8859-1"`, it captures `charset=iso-8859-1` as the charset value, not just `iso-8859-1`.

The problem is that the regex captures the value after the first "charset=", which happens to be another "charset=iso-8859-1". We need to modify the logic to handle cases where the charset value itself might start with "charset=".

Let me look more closely at the `getCharsetFromContentType` method:

```java
static String getCharsetFromContentType(String contentType) {
    if (contentType == null) return null;
    Matcher m = charsetPattern.matcher(contentType);
    if (m.find()) {
        String charset = m.group(1).trim();
        if (Charset.isSupported(charset)) return charset;
        charset = charset.toUpperCase(Locale.ENGLISH);
        if (Charset.isSupported(charset)) return charset;
        // if our advanced charset matching fails.... we just take the default
    }
    return null;
}
```

The issue is that when the regex matches `"charset=charset=iso-8859-1"`, it captures `"charset=iso-8859-1"` as the group, which is not a valid charset. We need to check if the captured value starts with "charset=" and extract the actual charset from there.

